==DVB-T television==
[[File:Croatia DVB-T Map.svg|left|thumb|[[DVB-T]] regions of Croatia|alt=Map of Croatia with digital TV regions]]
The first trial broadcasts of [[DVB-T]] signals began in May 2002 in Zagreb, and in 2008 the government developed an Analogue to Digital Television Broadcasting Switchover Strategy for the Republic of Croatia.<ref name="DVB-Strategy">{{cite web|publisher=[[Croatian Post and Electronic Communications Agency]]|url=http://www.hakom.hr/default.aspx?id=19|title=Strategies and Studies|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> In July 2008, this [[Government of Croatia]] announced that 106&nbsp;million [[Croatian kuna|kuna]] ({{circa}} 14.1&nbsp;million euros)<!-- According to [[MOS:CURRENCY|the Manual of Style]], the plural of "euro" is "euros" ("euroes" looks clumsy). --> were earmarked for the purpose.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Government of Croatia]]| url= http://www.vlada.hr/en/naslovnica/novosti_i_najave/2008/srpanj/predstavljena_strategija_prelaska_s_analognog_na_digitalno_emitiranje_televizijskog_programa|title=Croatia to convert to digital broadcasting in 2011|date=31 July 2008|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> The government-subsidized purchase of DVB-T receivers, distributing discount coupons worth 75 kuna ({{circa}} 10 euros) to subscribers of the [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] (HRT).<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Government of Croatia]]|url=http://www.vlada.hr/aktualne_teme_i_projekti/aktualne_teme/digitalna_televizija/kutak_za_gledatelje/kupon_za_popust_pri_kupnji_digitalnog_prijamnika_tijek_realizacije_od_podjele_kupona_do_isplate_trgovcima|language=Croatian|title=Kupon za popust pri kupnji digitalnog prijamnika <U+2013> tijek realizacije od podjele kupona do isplate trgovcima|trans_title=Digital receiver purchase discount coupons <U+2013> implementation from distribution of the coupons to reimbursement of retailers|date=29 June 2009|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> The first two [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexes]] (MUX A and MUX B) were introduced in April 2009, with the third (MUX D) introduced in July 2010. On 5 October 2010 the switch to DVB-T was virtually complete, as all major analog TV transmitters were phased out. The DVB-T transmissions in Croatia are all [[Standard-definition television|standard-definition]], [[MPEG-2]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i i veze]]|url=http://www.oiv.hr/broadcasting/terrestrial/dtv/dtv_en.aspx|title=DVB-T <U+2013> Television of the New Era|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref> MUX A is available to more than 98.5 percent<!-- According to MOS:PERCENT --> of the population of Croatia, and both MUX A and MUX B are available to more than 95 percent of population in each multiplex-allotment region. MUX D is available to approximately 90 percent of the population of Croatia, and at least 70 percent of the population in each of the allotment regions.<ref name="MUX-cover">{{cite web|publisher=[[Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i i veze]]|title=DTV <U+2013> Plan and status|url=http://www.oiv.hr/broadcasting/dvbt/plan-status/plan-status_en.aspx|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> There are 897,496 households (60.7 percent) in Croatia receiving DVB-T television only.<ref name="HAKOM-2011Q3">{{cite web|publisher=[[Croatian Post and Electronic Communications Agency]]|url=http://www.hakom.hr/UserDocsImages/2011/e-trziste/Q3-HR-2011-Tromjese<U+010D>ni%20usporedni%20podaci%20za%20tr<U+017E>i<U+0161>te%20elektroni<U+010D>kih%20komunikacija.pdf|format=PDF|language=Croatian|title=Tromjese<U+010D>ni usporedni podaci tr<U+017E>i<U+0161>ta elektroni<U+010D>kih komunikacija u Republici Hrvatskoj, tre<U+0107>e tromjese<U+010D>je 2011. godine|trans_title=Quarterly comparative data on electronic communications market in the Republic of Croatia, Third quarter of 2011|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> The terrestrial television infrastructure in Croatia is operated by [[Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i i veze]] d.o.o. (OIV). The company was established as an independent [[Legal personality|entity]] in 2002, when a division developing and maintaining electronic communications infrastructure was removed from the HRT corporate system.<ref name="HRT-Evolution"/><ref name="Oiv-About"/> As of January 2012, OIV operates and maintains 222 [[television transmitter]]s and [[broadcast relay station]]s.<ref name="Regions"/> 

There are nine main regions of digital TV allotments (encompassing larger portions of Croatia) and additional, geographically-small allotment areas designed for local broadcasters (typically covering a single city). The main DVB-T television allotment regions are assigned markings D1<U+2013>D9. The D1 region encompasses [[Osijek-Baranja County|Osijek-Baranja]] and [[Vukovar-Syrmia County|Vukovar-Syrmia]] counties, as well as parts of [[Brod-Posavina County]] east of [[Oprisavci]]. The D2 region covers the rest of Brod-Posavina County, [[Po<U+017E>ega-Slavonia County|Po<U+017E>ega-Slavonia]] and [[Virovitica-Podravina County|Virovitica-Podravina]] counties and nearly all of [[Bjelovar-Bilogora County]], except for an area north of the city of [[Bjelovar]] and part of [[Sisak-Moslavina County]] around the town of [[Novska]]. The D3 region includes a part of Bjelovar-Bilogora County not encompassed by the D2 region, as well as the territories of [[Koprivnica-Kri<U+017E>evci County|Koprivnica-Kri<U+017E>evci]], [[Vara<U+017E>din County|Vara<U+017E>din]] and [[Me<U+0111>imurje County|Me<U+0111>imurje]] counties. The D4 region includes Sisak-Moslavina County (except the area around Novska), [[Krapina-Zagorje County|Krapina-Zagorje]] and [[Zagreb County|Zagreb]] counties, the city of [[Zagreb]] and the northern part of [[Karlovac County]] (including [[Karlovac]] and [[Duga Resa]]).<ref name="Regions">{{cite web|publisher=Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i i veze|url=http://www.oiv.hr/broadcasting/tables/dtv_hr.aspx|language=Croatian|title=Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i digitalne televizije|trans_title=Digital television transmitters|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref>

[[File:Zgrada HRT Zagreb.jpg|right|thumb|[[Croatian Radiotelevision|HRT]] headquarters in Zagreb|alt=Large, low gray building housing Croatian Radiotelevision headquarters in Zagreb]]
The D5 region covers [[Istria County]] and [[Primorje-Gorski Kotar County]] (except parts of the county east of [[Ravna Gora, Croatia|Ravna Gora]] and the area around [[Novalja]] on the island of [[Pag (island)|Pag]]), but it includes the coastal areas of [[Lika-Senj County]] opposite the islands of [[Krk]] and [[Rab]]. The D6 region encompasses parts of Primorje-Gorski Kotar and Lika-Senj counties outside the D4 and D5 regions, except for parts of the latter (south of [[Lovinac]]) and coastal parts of the same county opposite the island of Pag. Those two areas are a part of the D7 region, along with [[Zadar County|Zadar]] and [[<U+0160>ibenik-Knin County|<U+0160>ibenik-Knin]] counties. The D8 region includes the entire [[Split-Dalmatia County]] as well as parts of [[Dubrovnik-Neretva County]] around [[Plo<U+010D>e]] and [[Metkovi<U+0107>]], a part of [[Pelje<U+0161>ac]] peninsula west of [[Dubrava, Dubrovnik-Neretva County|Dubrava]] and the islands of [[Kor<U+010D>ula]] and [[Lastovo]]. The D9 region encompasses the rest of Dubrovnik-Neretva County.<ref name="Regions"/>

[[File:Studio hrt 4 250409.jpg|left|thumb|HRT's Anton Marti studio|alt=Small photo of unused TV studio, with cameras covered]]
There are also 12 local DVB-T television allotment regions, covering specific cities and their immediate surroundings. Those are d11 in [[Osijek]], d21 in [[Slavonski Brod]], d31 covering [[Vara<U+017E>din]] and [[<U+010C>akovec]], d44 encompassing Zagreb and [[Velika Gorica]], d45 in [[Jastrebarsko]], d46 covering Karlovac and Duga Resa, d53 encompassing [[Rijeka]], [[Crikvenica]], [[Novi Vinodolski]] and most of the island of Krk, d54 in [[Pula]] and [[Rovinj]], d71 in [[Zadar]], d72 in [[<U+0160>ibenik]], d82 covering [[Split, Croatia|Split]], [[Trogir]], [[Omi<U+0161>]], the island of [[<U+0160>olta]] and a large part of the island of [[Bra<U+010D>]], and d91 in [[Dubrovnik]].<ref name="Regions"/>

When Italian DVB-T broadcasting started in December 2010 [[Co-channel interference|interference]] was observed in northwest parts of [[Istria]], and later in areas around [[Zadar]] and [[<U+0160>ibenik]]. The interference was caused by the use of [[Frequency coordination|frequencies assigned]] to Croatia by Italian transmitters and excessive transmitter power. A complaint was filed by the Croatian regulator of the DVB-T market, the [[Croatian Post and Electronic Communications Agency]] (HAKOM), with the Italian authorities.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Nacional (weekly)]]|url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/97741/hakom-intenzivno-radi-na-uklanjanju-smetnji-u-digitalnom-tv-signalu-na-podrucju-istre|language=Croatian|title=HAKOM intenzivno radi na uklanjanju smetnji u digitalnom TV signalu na podru<U+010D>ju Istre|trans_title=HAKOM strives to remedy interference of digital TV signal in Istria|date=16 December 2010|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|language=Croatian|title=Ne<U+0107>emo dopustiti da Dalmacija i Istra gledaju samo talijanske programe|trans_title=We shall not leave Dalmatia and Istria to receive only Italian channels|author=Sanja Stapi<U+0107>|date=9 February 2011|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/128942/Default.aspx|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> OIV installed additional transmitters in the affected areas to strengthen its signal coverage and reduce interference by February 2011 at a cost of 1&nbsp;million kuna ({{circa}} 133,000 euros).<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i i veze|url=http://www.oiv.hr/tvrtka/vijesti/vijest_hr.aspx?id=553|language=Croatian|title=Priop<U+0107>enje uprave OIV-a na probleme u prijemu DVB-T signala zbog smetnji iz Italije|trans_title=Communique of OIV management regarding problems in DVB-T signal reception caused by interference from Italy|date=8 February 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> Although [[Italian Minister of Economic Development]] [[Paolo Romani]] announced in August 2011 that the problems should be resolved shortly (a transmitter causing interference was shut down and the power of several others was reduced),<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Novi list]]|language=Croatian|url=http://www.novilist.hr/Scena/TV/Rijesen-problem-ometanja-digitalnog-signala-hrvatskih-televizija-iz-odasiljaca-s-podrucja-Italije?articlesrclink=related|title=Rije<U+0161>en problem ometanja digitalnog signala hrvatskih televizija iz oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>a s podru<U+010D>ja Italije|trans_title=Problem caused by interference of Croatian television digital signal by Italy based transmitters resolved|date=26 August 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> the situation was not completely resolved throughout 2011 and the [[International Telecommunication Union]]'s [[Radio Regulations Board]] became involved in the process.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]]|url=http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=ispis&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=144087&cHash=db91ec7387|title=Smetnje u Istri <U+2013> rje<U+0161>enje na vidiku?|trans_title=Interference in Istria <U+2013> resolution at hand?|date=21 December 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> In the meantime, other technical solutions were devised and implemented (in addition to the emergency transmitters) in order to improve digital-television-signal reception.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Glas Istre]]|url=http://www.glasistre.hr/istra/vijest/341436|language=Croatian|title=Vodi<U+010D> do boljeg TV signala|trans_title=A guide to a better TV signal|date=22 August 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref>

===Nationwide channels===
[[File:Dobro jutro Hrvatska Leib i Novokmet.JPG|right|thumb|Studio set of HRT's morning show ''Dobro jutro Hrvatska'' in February 2008|Croatian morning-show studio, with woman seated on sofa and man behind her standing at counter]]
As of December 2011 there are ten nationwide [[free-to-air]] DVB-T television channels, with HRT, [[Nova TV (Croatia)|Nova TV]] and [[RTL Televizija]] operating two channels each and the remaining four operated by the [[Croatian Olympic Committee]], Kapital Net d.o.o., Author d.o.o. companies and the government's Central State Administrative Office for e-Croatia. All ten DVB-T television channels are [[free-to-air]] and privately owned, except for HRT's [[HRT 1]] and [[HRT 2]] channels and the [[Moja uprava]] channel (which are [[Public broadcasting|publicly-owned broadcasters]]).<ref name="OIV-DVBTable">{{cite web|publisher=[[Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i i veze]]|url=http://www.oiv.hr/broadcasting/tables/dtv_channel_hr.aspx|title=Popis programa i servisa digitalne televizije|trans_title=List of Digital Television Programmes and Services|language=Croatian|accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref> [[Doma TV]] is part of the Nova TV group.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Doma TV]]|url=http://domatv.hr/stranica/o_nama/|title=O name|trans_title=About us|language=Croatian|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> Since 2007 television [[audience measurement]] is conducted by the [[Nielsen Company]] using 1,086 [[peoplemeter]]s, and it is applied to terrestrial, cable and satellite TV. As of January 2012 HRT, RTL Televizija and Nova TV are using the service.<ref name="JL-Peoplemeter">{{cite news|newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]]|url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/mjerac-gledanosti-programa/181945/|title=Mjera<U+010D> gledanosti programa|trans_title=Program audience meter|language=Croatian|date=12 July 2007|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref><ref name="Nielsen">{{cite web|publisher=[[Nielsen Company]]|url=http://www.agbnielsen.net/whereweare/dynPage.asp?lang=english&id=307&country=Croatia|title=TAM Overview|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref>

HRT 1, Nova TV and RTL Televizija channels' programmes are not specialized and comprise [[News program|news]], a variety of scripted and unscripted entertainment, as well as [[Television documentary|documentaries]]. HRT2, Doma TV and [[RTL 2 (Croatia)|RTL 2]] channels, carry similar type of programmes, except for absence of news.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=t-portal.hr|url=http://www.tportal.hr/showtime/tv/83590/sto-nam-donosi-jesen-na-televiziji.html|title=<U+0160>to nam donosi jesen na televiziji?|language=Croatian|trans_title=What will autumn bring on the TV?|date=27 August 2010|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> In addition, Croatian Radiotelevision is legally required to produce and broadcast programmes covering education of youths, aimed at the [[Croatian diaspora]], national minorities in Croatia, preservation of [[Cultural heritage|cultural]] and [[natural heritage]], protection of the environment, promotion of democracy and [[civil society]], and support national production of films, television programme and music.<ref name="HRT-Act"/> Other nationwide channels are specialized providing informational programmes, covering sports or music.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Ve<U+010D>ernji list]]|language=Croatian|url=http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/nista-novo-pet-novih-programa-clanak-229006|title=Ni<U+0161>ta novo na pet novih programa|trans_title=Nothing new on five new channels|date=16 December 2010|authors=Bo<U+017E>ena Matijevi<U+0107>, Andro Bernardi<U+0107>, Damir Mrvec|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>

