===HDTV and DVB-T2===
[[File:Hrt rez 250409.jpg|right|thumb|Television director's desk at HRT|alt=TV director's console, with many monitors on wall]]
Experimental [[high-definition television]] (HDTV) broadcasting began in Zagreb in March 2007; it was expanded to Split, Rijeka and Osijek in 2008. Experimental HDTV broadcasting ended in February 2011.<ref name="DVB-experimental">{{cite web|publisher=Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i i veze|url=http://www.oiv.hr/broadcasting/terrestrial/dtv/dtv_en.aspx|title=DVB-T <U+2013> Television of the New Era|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> There were two experimental HDTV channels, operated by Croatian Radiotelevision and Nova TV. Pursuant to the digital television switchover developed by the Government of Croatia, broadcasting of DVB-T HDTV channels was conducted in [[MPEG-4]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]]|url=http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=173&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=7457&cHash=9ca28de250|language=Croatian|title=DVB-T oda<U+0161>iljanje u HDTV kvaliteti|trans_title=DVB-T transmitting in HDTV quality|date=4 February 2011|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Nova TV (Croatia)]]|url=http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/znanost-it/produkcija-nove-tv-o-posljednjem-kriku-hd-tehnologije.html|language=Croatian|title=Produkcija Nove TV u posljednjem kriku HD tehnologije|trans_title=Nova TV production using the latest HD technology|date=6 August 2010|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> On 11 October 2011 experimental [[DVB-T2]] broadcasting began in Zagreb, using [[H.264/MPEG-4 AVC]] coding and a [[conditional access]] system.<ref name="DVBT2-experimental">{{cite web|publisher=Oda<U+0161>ilja<U+010D>i i veze|url=http://www.oiv.hr/tvrtka/vijesti/vijest_en.aspx?id=748|title=DVB-T2 experimental broadcasting|date=14 October 2011|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref>

===Multiplexes===
There are three active [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexes]] (MUX) in Croatia. MUX A and MUX B are reserved for nationwide channels, and MUX D is used for channels broadcast locally and nationwide. MUX A broadcasts HRT 1, HRT 2 , Nova TV, RTL and ''Moja uprava'' channels. MUX B broadcasts RTL2 and Doma TV. MUX D broadcasts three nationwide channels<U+2014>Sportska Televizija, Kapital Network (KN) and CMC<U+2014>in addition to local TV channels.<ref name="OIV-DVBTable"/>

A competition for two channels in MUX B was announced in July 2010, and HAKOM received offers for the following channels: RTL 2, Doma TV, OBN and KN. Finally, licenses were given to RTL 2 and Doma TV.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Ve<U+010D>ernji list]]|url=http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/na-dvije-nove-televizije-pocetku-tek-tri-nove-domace-emisije-clanak-233218|language=Croatian|title=Na dvije nove televizije u po<U+010D>etku tek tri nove doma<U+0107>e emisije|trans_title=Two new television channels with only three new nationally produced shows|date=28 December 2010|authors=Bo<U+017E>ena Matijevi<U+0107>, Antonio Mandir|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref> RTL2 and Doma TV began broadcasting on 2 January 2011. Licences for broadcasting in the national segment of Mux D were given to Croatian Music Channel (CMC), Sportska Televizija (owned by the [[Croatian Olympic Committee]]) and KN in December 2010. They started broadcasting in late March and early April 2011.<ref name="OIV-DVBTable"/> KN was originally broadcast in MUX B; as holder of a [[television license|license]] for a testing period, they won an experimental 6-month period license (and later switched to MUX D, which carries both local and nationwide services simultaneously). MUX B also carries two new channels<U+2014>HRT 3 and HRT 4. The two are expected to begin broadcasting by the end of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Croatian Radiotelevision|url=http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=186&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=141139&cHash=6a0075ced0|language=Croatian|title=Programska mjesta HRT3 i HRT4 u mre<U+017E>i MUX B|trans_title=HRT3 and HRT4 channel slots in MUX B network|date=1 December 2011|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref>

