==IPTV, cable and satellite television==
[[File:Business Centre T-Com Zagreb 2 - Architect Marijan Turkulin.jpg|right|thumb|Headquarters of [[T-Hrvatski Telekom]], the largest [[IPTV]] provider in Croatia|alt=T-Hrvatski Telekom headquarters, a tall building with a red ''T'' on the side]]
IPTV is recording rapid market growth; between 2009 and 2010, the number of households subscribed to an [[IPTV]] service grew by 23 percent to nearly 300,000. In terms of IPTV density Croatia is the fifth-ranked market in the world, trailing only Singapore, Hong Kong, Cyprus and Estonia.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Vjesnik]]|url=http://www.vjesnik.hr/Article.aspx?ID=8B772F4B-4D0D-4896-9343-8C44E8F410A5|archivedate=14 June 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/68Pd2K8ub|title=Telekomi u minusu zbog smanjene potro<U+0161>nje korisnika|trans_title=Telecom operators in red due to reduced user spending|language=Croatian|date=27 February 2011|author=Marinko Petkovi<U+0107>|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> The number rose further by the third quarter of 2011 to a total of 349,138 households, representing 23.6 percent of Croatian households. At the same time there were 144,439 households with cable television connections and 104,635 households with satellite television reception (representing 9.8  and 7.1 percent of households in Croatia, respectively).<ref name="HAKOM-2011Q3"/> The leading IPTV provider in Croatia is [[T-Hrvatski Telekom]] with its MaxTV service, while [[Vipnet]]-owned B.net is the leading cable-television provider in the country.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]]|title=Udar na HT: Vipnet kupio B.net za 93 milijuna eura i u<U+0161>ao na novo tr<U+017E>i<U+0161>te |language=Croatian |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/telekomunikacijsko-trziste--udar-na-ht--vipnet-kupio-b-net-za-93-milijuna-eura/952036/|trans_title=Action against HT: Vipnet buys B.net for 93 million euro and enters a new market|date=8 June 2011|author= Merita Arslani|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> Since 2009, some providers offer HDTV reception of IPTV channels.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[PC Chip]]|url=http://www.pcchip.hr/zapocinje-komercijalno-koristenje-maxtv-hd-usluge/|language=Croatian|title=Zapo<U+010D>inje komercijalno kori<U+0161>tenje MAXtv HD usluge|trans_title=Commercial use of MAXtv HD service starts|date=3 April 2009|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref> The IPTV and satellite-TV providers normally carry all channels otherwise available in DVB-T, with additional channels (produced in Croatia and abroad) available through various subscription plans. A significant proportion of the foreign channels are localized through [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing]] or [[Subtitle (captioning)|subtitles]]. The two largest IPTV and cable TV providers offer 31 channels produced in Croatia (or specifically for Croatia), in addition to those broadcasting in DVB-T.<ref name="Maxtv1">{{cite web|publisher=[[T-Hrvatski Telekom]]|url=http://www.t-com.hr/privatni/televizija/maxtv/paketi/osnovni_extra.asp|title=Osnovni Extra paket
|trans_title=Basic Extra Package|language=Croatian|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref><ref name="Maxtv2">{{cite web|publisher=[[T-Hrvatski Telekom]]|url=http://www.t-com.hr/privatni/televizija/maxtv/paketi/sportski.asp|title=Sportski paket|trans_title=Sports Package|language=Croatian|accessdate=31 December 2011}}</ref><ref name="Bnet">{{cite web|publisher=B.net|title=Ponuda programa|trans_title=Programming available|language=Croatian|url=http://www.bnet.hr/televizija/ponuda_programa|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> Viewership of cable and satellite TV channels broadcast by HRT, RTL Televizija, Nova TV and Z1 Televizija is measured by Nielsen Company peoplemeters.<ref name="JL-Peoplemeter"/><ref name="Nielsen"/> 

