==Market regulation==
The television industry in Croatia is regulated by the [[Croatian Post and Electronic Communications Agency]] (HAKOM). HAKOM was established by the Electronic Communications Act of 26 June 2008; pursuant to Article 5 of the act, HAKOM is tasked with promoting and safeguarding market competition and the interests of service users in the field of electronic communication services and infrastructure, while contributing to the development of the internal market of the [[European Union]].<ref name="NN-HAKOM">{{cite news|newspaper=[[Narodne Novine]]|url=http://narodne-novine.nn.hr/clanci/sluzbeni/2008_06_73_2420.html|language=Croatian|title=Zakon o elektroni<U+010D>kim komunikacijama|trans_title=Electronic Communications Act|date=26 June 2008|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> HAKOM's goals include ensuring sustainable development of the electronic communications market at affordable prices for consumers, providing fair conditions for return on investment in the market and contributing to the quality of life in Croatia.<ref name="HAKOM-Mission">{{cite web|publisher=[[Croatian Post and Electronic Communications Agency]]|title=Mission, values, goals|accessdate=1 January 2012|url=http://www.hakom.hr/default.aspx?id=203}}</ref> Further regulation of the television is performed by the Electronic Media Council, which enacts mandatory regulation applying to both state-run and privately owned broadcasters based in Croatia. One such regulation, aimed at protection of [[Minor (law)|minors]], restricts depictions of violence, sexual intercourse, [[profanity]], use of intoxicating substances and tobacco and other scenes which may be harmful to development of minors between seven in the morning and nine, ten or eleven in the evening, depending on rating of specific programme&mdash;advising that the programme is not suitable for persons under 12, 15 or 18 years of age respectively. The restriction does not apply to educational, documentary, science or news programming.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Narodne novine]]|url=http://narodne-novine.nn.hr/clanci/sluzbeni/2010_05_60_1957.html|language=Croatian|title=Pravilnik o za<U+0161>titi maloljetnika|trans_title=Regulation on protection of minors|date=13 May 2010|accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref>

HAKOM grants, evaluates and revokes [[broadcast license]]s for all forms of electronic communications in Croatia, approves mergers of communications-industry companies, imposes fines on those who are found to be in breach of applicable regulation and conducts constant supervision of the industry.<ref name="NN-HAKOM"/>

==Language localisation==
National legislation requires that all television programmes broadcasts in Croatia are made in [[Croatian language]] or with appropriate translations either using [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing]] or [[Subtitle (captioning)|subtitling]]. In general, all foreign programming is subtitled, except for cartoons and narrated parts of [[Documentary film|documentaries]] and similar programmes. An attempt to change this was made by Nova TV in 2006, when a [[soap opera]] was dubbed, but the move provoked negative response from viewers and critics, causing the experiment to be abandoned.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|url=http://arhiv.slobodnadalmacija.hr/20061207/reflektor03.asp|title=<U+0160>varci (ne)<U+0107>e "<U+0161>prehati" hrvatski|language=Croatian|trans_title=Schwarzie will (not) "sprechen" Croatian|date=7 December 2006|author=Sini<U+0161>a Pavi<U+0107>|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> The legislation does not provide for [[Mutual intelligibility|mutually intelligible]] languages. That led to formal requests made by the Electronic Media Council demanding [[language localisation]] of television programmes made in [[Serbian language]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Ve<U+010D>ernji list]]|language=Croatian|title='Ko nas bre prevodi?' <U+2013> Vije<U+0107>e zna da je zakon lo<U+0161>, ali ga ipak provodi|trans_title="Who's translating us?" - The Council knows that the legislation is poor, but it enforces it anyway|date=27 January 2012|author=Milena Zajovi<U+0107>|accessdate=5 July 2012url=http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/ko-nas-bre-prevodi-vijece-zna-da-je-zakon-los-ali-ga-ipak-provodi-clanak-370505}}</ref> Ultimately, that issue was resolved through subtitling using [[teletext]] service normally used for [[closed captioning]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Mozaik/tabid/80/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/163322/Default.aspx|language=Croatian|title=Eureka! HRT na<U+0161>ao rje<U+0161>enje za sporno titlovanje srpskih filmova|trans_title=Eureka! Croatian Radiotelevision finds solution to disputed subtitling of Serbian films|date=2 February 2012|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>

==Social impact==
Television in Croatia, as all other [[Media of Croatia|media in the country]] are criticised for lack of balance of global issues and trends on one hand and national topics covered on the other. All major television networks in Croatia are generally thought to be under excessive influence of [[commercialism]]. This is viewed through international ownership structures of the privately owned television broadcasters having little regard for promotion of national culture and social issues, as well as through efforts of the state-run HRT to attract advertisers through programming that is thought to appeal to the viewers the best in spite of regulation of programming content and restricted advertising at the HRT.<ref name="Malovi<U+0107>">{{cite journal|journal=Kolo|publisher=[[Matica hrvatska]]|issue=2|year=2005|issn=1331-0992|author=Stjepan Malovi<U+0107>|title=Odnos masovnih medija i kulture|trans_title=Relationship of mass media and culture|language=Croatian|url=http://www.matica.hr/Kolo/kolo2005_2.nsf/AllWebDocs/smalovic|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref><ref name="<U+010C>erkez">{{cite journal|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=64293&lang=en|language=Croatian|title=Osnovna obilje<U+017E>ja medijske komunikacije u demokratskoj kulturi|trans_title=The basic characteristics of media communications in a democratic culture|author=Ivana <U+010C>erkez|volume=18|issue=1|month=March|year=2009|pages=28-45|journal=Socijalna ekologija: Journal for Environmental Thought and Sociological Research|publisher=Croatian Sociological Society, Institute of Sociology at Faculty of Philosophy, [[University of Zagreb]]|issn=1330-0113|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> The HRT is limited by a special legislation regulating that broadcaster to four minutes of advertising in [[prime time]] period between 6 and 10 in the evening.<ref name="HRT-Act">{{cite web|publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]]|language=Croatian|url=http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=96560&cHash=c7a3d3a725|title=Prihva<U+0107>en Zakon o HRT-u|trans_title=HRT Act passed|date=3 December 2010|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> On the other hand, the HRT receives income from a fee charged to owners of [[television set]]s in Croatia in the amount of 1.5% of average monthly net [[wage]] in Croatia.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Narodne novine]]|url=http://narodne-novine.nn.hr/clanci/sluzbeni/304950.html|title=Zakon o Hrvatskoj radioteleviziji|language=Croatian|trans_title=Croatian Radiotelevision Act|date=19 February 2003|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> In 2012, the fee charged is 80&nbsp;[[Croatian kuna|kuna]]s ({{circa}} 10.60&nbsp;[[Euro]]s).<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]]|url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/167662/Default.aspx|language=Croatian|title=Odobreni ve<U+0107>i prosvjedi; Milanovi<U+0107>: Brodogradnja <U+0107>e opstati; HRT ostaje na 80 kn|trans_title=Larger protests approved; Milanovi<U+0107>: Shipbuilding shall survive; HRT remains at 80 kuna|date=15 March 2012|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> In 2010, annual income of the HRT generated by the fee amounted to 1.2&nbsp;billion kunas ({{circa}} 160&nbsp;million Euros).<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[Ve<U+010D>ernji list]]|language=Croatian|url=http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/drzava-hrt-u-dala-vise-nego-sto-su-svi-drugi-zaradili-oglasima-clanak-204368|title=Dr<U+017E>ava HRT-u dala vi<U+0161>e nego <U+0161>to su svi drugi zaradili na oglasima|trans_title=The state gave the HRT more than everyone else earned through advertising|date=17 October 2010|author=Lidija Kiseljak|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>

Even though social impact of television in Croatia is considered to be imperfect and that of variable quality, television is important in the society because it offers a way for [[non-governmental organization]]s to communicate their concerns to the public and to criticise the [[Government of Croatia|government]] and other aspects of [[politics of Croatia]].<ref name="<U+010C>erkez"/> Television is the most widespread source of information in Croatia&mdash;on average 57% of the [[population of Croatia]] uses television as their primary source of information. That percentage varies significantly by [[List of regions of Croatia|geographic region]]&mdash;from 43% in Zagreb and areas surrounding the capital to 79% in [[Slavonia]]&mdash;but in every region it surpasses all other sources of information, the second most widely used source of information being the [[Internet]] averaging at 19%.<ref name="Primary">{{cite web|publisher=[[Poslovni dnevnik]]|url=http://www.poslovni.hr/vijesti/hrvati-najvise-koriste-televiziju-kao-izvor-informiranja-174661.aspx|language=Croatian|title=Hrvati najvi<U+0161>e koriste televiziju kao izvor informiranja|trans_title=Croats most often use television as a source of information|date=15 March 2011|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> There are 1.584&nbsp;million registered television sets in the country.<ref name="yearbook">{{Croatia Yearbook 2011|page=495|chapter=Culture, arts and sprot|author=}}</ref>

